*1221
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (1) Defendant did not name Ms. Story as a witness in its initial disclosures or discovery responses; and (2) the Story Declaration does not sufficiently explain Ms. Story\rquote s foundation of personal knowledge. Plaintiff further argues that the Story Declaration is a \u8220\'3fsham\u8221\'3f declaration that recites facts contradictory to Defendant\rquote s prior testimony with the sole purpose of defeating summary judgment. Defendant responds that since Ms. Story\rquote s name was disclosed in its responses to interrogatories, Defendant was not required to supplement its disclosures and discovery responses pursuant to Rule 26(e)(1)(A). Ms. Story\rquote s name was mentioned twice in Plaintiff\rquote s discovery responses: as a person who assisted in preparing answers to Plaintiff\rquote s first set of interrogatories (dkt. # 32 at 10:3-5), and again as the verification signatory for answers to Plaintiff\rquote s second set of interrogatories (
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
id.
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 at 42.) Having disclosed Ms. Story as a potential witness in writing during the discovery process pursuant to Rule 26(e)(1)(A), Defendant argues that no further supplemental disclosure was needed.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
