{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
In its Response, Defendant cites conflicting testimony as to whether Plaintiff delivered a letter disclosing her status to a HASCO employee. (Resp. at 9; McIntire Decl. at \u182\'3f 10, Ex. 19; Repass Decl., Ex. Q at 2.) While there is conflicting testimony as to whether this letter was delivered, the undisputed facts show that prior to this event Plaintiff represented to HASCO that she was a \u8220\'3fVAWA victim.\u8221\'3f On February 7, 2020, HASCO employee Kristen Whittaker visited Plaintiff in the Unit. (McIntire Decl. at \u182\'3f 13, Ex. 6.) Though the exact contents of this interaction are disputed, Defendant admitted that Plaintiff\rquote s status as a domestic violence victim under VAWA was discussed. Following this event, Ms. Whittaker wrote to colleagues that Plaintiff \u8220\'3fhas documentation of being a VAWA victim.\u8221\'3f (Crain Decl., Ex. 8 at 2.) At her deposition, Ms. Whittaker similarly testified that \u8220\'3f[Plaintiff] informed me that she has documentation of being a VAWA victim.\u8221\'3f (Crain Decl., Ex. 14 at 16-17.) Though Ms. Whittaker also testified that she did not actually know whether Plaintiff was a \u8220\'3fVAWA victim,\u8221\'3f that she asked Plaintiff to provide documentation, and that Plaintiff never followed up with documentation, these facts do not negate Plaintiff\rquote s 
}
